# Code Quality Rules

## Comments vs. Methods

**Prefer self-explanatory method names over comments.**

Instead of explaining code with comments, extract the code into a well-named method that describes its intent.

### Bad:
```typescript
// Set tablist role and orientation
if (!this.tablist.getAttribute('role')) {
  this.tablist.setAttribute('role', 'tablist');
}
this.tablist.setAttribute('aria-orientation', this.config.orientation);
```

### Good:
```typescript
private setTablistAttributes(): void {
  if (!this.tablist.getAttribute('role')) {
    this.tablist.setAttribute('role', 'tablist');
  }
  this.tablist.setAttribute('aria-orientation', this.config.orientation);
}
```

### When to use comments:
- **Why**, not **what**: Explain non-obvious decisions or constraints
- **External references**: Link to specs (e.g., WAI-ARIA APG)
- **Public API documentation**: JSDoc for exported functions/classes
- **Complex algorithms**: When the logic itself is inherently complex

### When NOT to use comments:
- Describing what the code does (use method names instead)
- Step-by-step explanations (extract to methods)
- Section headers (organize into methods/classes)
